  1. (4pts) Now Professor Waggoner would like to understand if cp is associated with other variables in the data. He has the following questions:
  • Do you think cp and sex are independent?
  • Do you think cp and target are independent?

Run statistical analyses that allow you to answer both of these questions. State Yes or No for each question, and explain in 1-2 sentences how you arrived at your answer using your statistical analyses (which you should include in this part as well).

Both of these questions ask us to assess if two categorical variables are independent. At this point, bells (or some other musical instrument of your choice) should be ringing in your head: The most appropriate analysis is a chi-squared test. Here are the corresponding chi-squared tests:

chisq.test(table(heart$cp, heart$sex))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(heart$cp, heart$sex)
## X-squared = 6.8221, df = 3, p-value = 0.07779
chisq.test(table(heart$cp, heart$target))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(heart$cp, heart$target)
## X-squared = 81.686, df = 3, p-value < 2.2e-16

Now we’ll answer the two questions:

  • Do you think cp and sex are independent?

Yes. We see the p-value for this chi-squared test is 0.08; this is just above the traditional \(\alpha = 0.05\) value, but nonetheless we fail to reject the null hypothesis that these variables are independent, thereby concluding that cp and sex are independent.

  • Do you think cp and target are independent?

No. We see the p-value for this chi-squared test is quite small and certainly less than 0.05. Thus, we reject the null hypothesis that these variables are independent, thereby concluding that cp and target are dependent.

mosaicplot(table(heart$cp, heart$target), shade = TRUE)

We see that there are an unusually high number of subjects with cp = 0 and target = 0; this corresponds to low-severity chest pain and no heart condition. For the linear regression, we see a positive trend, suggesting that higher ages are associated with higher oldpeak values. This is intuitive, since we would expect that people with higher ages would (unfortunately) have worse heart health.

Meanwhile, for the quadratic regression, the trend is fairly similar there’s still a positive trend, where higher ages are associated with higher oldpeak values - but now we see that estimated oldpeak values tend to “plateau” or “level off” for high ages.

Finally, for the loess curve, the overall trend between age and oldpeak is much less clear here: We see that the estimated oldpeak is about the same for ages below 50, for ages between 50 and 65 we see the positive trend we noted in Parts A and B, and there is a downward trend for ages above 65 (meaning older age is associated with lower oldpeak values). This is perhaps intuitive: Most fatal heart conditions occur between ages 50 and 65, so if you survive past 65, you may be less likely to have severe heart conditions (because if you, counterfactually, had severe heart conditions, you may not have made it past 65).   1. (6pts) Professor E. Korman is interested in the linear regression you plotted in Parts A and B. Here we’ll use the lm() function to run the linear regression between age and oldpeak that we visualized in Part A and Part B:

summary(lm(oldpeak ~ age, data = heart))
##

We see that the p-value for the slope of age is 0.0002, and the estimated slope is positive (0.03). Thus, the positive trend that we saw in Part A is indeed statistically significant: We formally conclude that there is a non-zero slope for age, at least for this regression model, because we reject the null hypothesis that the slope is 0.

Meanwhile, here are our interepretations of the two estimated coefficients in this linear regression model:

  • We see that the estimated intercept is -0.42. This means that the estimated mean oldpeak for age = 0 subjects is -0.42. (Note: No, it does not make sense to consider age = 0 subjects, but this is nonetheless the correct interpretation of the intercept.)

  • We see that the estimated slope for age is 0.027. This means that the mean oldpeak is estimated to increase by 0.027 for every one-year increase in age.

  1. (5pts) Looking at your answer in Part C, Professor Korman gets confused. She says, “It looks like this model is estimating that the average oldpeak for some people is negative, which doesn’t even make sense. Why is your model giving these nonsense estimates?” Answer the following questions for Professor Korman:
  • For what ages (in whole numbers) does the linear model estimate that oldpeak is negative?

For ages 15 and below the model estimates oldpeak to be negative. To understand how we arrived at this answer, note that the estimated oldpeak for any given age is:

\(-0.420048 + 0.026848 \cdot \text{age}\)

Setting this equal to zero and solving for age, we get:

\(age = 0.420048/0.026848 = 15.64541 \approx 15\)

Here we rounded down because age = 16 results in a very slightly positive esitmated oldpeak. Thus, for ages 15 and less, we do indeed estimate oldpeak to be negative.

  • Explain to Professor Korman in 1-3 sentences why this model may estimate oldpeak to be negative for some ages, even though we don’t observe any negative oldpeak measurements in the data.

Note that we only observe subjects as young as 29 in the heart dataset; thus, any predictions of oldpeak for ages 15 and below are based entirely on extrapolation from the linear regression model. Large extrapolations from linear regression models (and other regression models) can lead to nonsensical estimates like this, which is why it is generally dangerous to trust predictions based on extrapolations.

  1. (6pts) Finally, Professor Korman wants to assess the Normality assumption in linear regression. This is equivalent to assessing if the residuals are Normally distributed. Assess this assumption in two ways:

Below we copy-and-pasted the Plot3 code, but then we set color = sex and shape = target (instead of the reverse). This gave us the following plot:

ggplot(heart,
    aes(x = chol, y = thalach, color = sex)) +
geom_point(aes(shape = target)) +
geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE) + labs(title = "Plot 3 New")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Note that the regression lines visualized here are exactly the same as the lines in the original Plot3, but now colored by sex. Thus, we can see that the downward-sloping line corresponds to sex = 1 (male) subjects, and the almost-flat line corresponds to sex = 0 (female) subjects.

Note that Plot4 is colored by the target variable, and we noted in Part A that Plot4 visualizes a regression line for each target and sex combination. Thus, the two blue lines correspond to target = 1 subjects and the two red lines correspond to target = 0 subjects; however, we don’t know which sex subset each line corresponds to. To determine this, we can use the exact same approach as Part B, but for the target = 1 and target = 0 subsets of the data.

Below we make two plots: One for target = 1 subjects and one for target = 0 subjects. In each plot, regression lines are colored by sex.

First, here’s the target = 1 plot:

ggplot(target1Data,

Looking back at Plot4, we can see that these are indeed the two blue regression lines in Plot4 (because both lines are above thalach = 150).

ggplot(target0Data,

  • Which subset of data does the bottom blue line represent in Plot4?

This represents target = 1 and sex = 0 (female) subjects.

This represents target = 0 and sex = 0 (female) subjects.

This represents target = 0 and sex = 1 (male) subjects.

Answer the following questions for Professor Matsubara:

  • Which of the four plots (Plot1, Plot2, Plot3, or Plot4) is visualizing the regression model that Professor Matsubara just ran? Explain how you arrived at your answer in 1-2 sentences.

This regression model is being visualized by Plot3. Plot3 has separate regression lines for each sex group (as we discussed in Part A), and here we are including sex in the regression to obtain a different intercept and slope for each sex group (as we elaborate on below).

To help with answering the questions below: Note that this linear regression is making the following modeling specification:

\[\text{thalach} \sim N(\beta_0 + \beta_C \cdot \text{chol} + \beta_M \cdot I_M + \beta_{CM} \cdot \text{chol} \cdot I_M, \sigma^2)\]

where \(I_M = 1\) for male (sex = 1) subjects and \(I_M = 0\) for female (sex = 0) subjects. Therefore, according to this model, the mean thalach for male subjects is:

\[(\beta_0 + \beta_M) + (\beta_C + \beta_{CM}) \cdot \text{chol}\]

and the mean thalach for female subjects is:

\[\beta_0 + \beta_C \cdot \text{chol}\]

  • According to the above model, what is the estimated intercept for female subjects? What is the estimated slope for female subjects? (Your answer should be just two numbers; do your best to show your work.)

From the above, we can see that the intercept for female subjects is \(\beta_0\); the estimate for this is 148.62. Meanwhile, the slope is \(\beta_C\); the estimate is 0.01.

  • According to the above model, what is the estimated intercept for male subjects? What is the estimated slope for male subjects? (Your answer should be just two numbers; do your best to show your work.)

From the above, we can see that the intercept for male subjects is \(\beta_0 + \beta_M\); the estimate for this is \(148.62 + 7.03 = 155.65\). Meanwhile, the slope is \(\beta_C + \beta_{CM}\); the estimate is \(0.01 - 0.04 = -0.03\).
